# Code Style & Naming Conventions

## C# Conventions

- Use latest C# features when appropriate
- Enable nullable reference types
- Use `async`/`await` for I/O and database operations
- Use `using` statements for disposable resources
- Follow Microsoft C# coding conventions

## Naming Standards

- Classes: PascalCase (e.g., `ConnectionManager`)
- Methods: PascalCase (e.g., `ExecuteQuery`)
- Private fields: _camelCase with underscore (e.g., `_connectionString`)
- Properties: PascalCase (e.g., `ConnectionStatus`)
- Local variables: camelCase (e.g., `connectionString`)
- Constants: PascalCase (e.g., `DefaultTimeout`)
- Async methods: Suffix with `Async` (e.g., `ExecuteQueryAsync`)

## Exception Handling Pattern

```csharp
try
{
    await PerformOperationAsync();
}
catch (SpecificException ex)
{
    Logger.Error(ex, "Specific error during {Operation}", operationName);
    throw;
}
catch (Exception ex)
{
    Logger.Error(ex, "Unexpected error during {Operation}", operationName);
    throw;
}
```

## XML Documentation

Document all public classes and methods:

```csharp
/// <summary>
/// Brief description of the class/method purpose.
/// </summary>
/// <param name="paramName">Description of the parameter.</param>
/// <returns>Description of the return value.</returns>
public async Task<DataTable> ExecuteQueryAsync(string sql)
```

## Code Review Checklist

Before committing code, verify:
- [ ] Target framework is current (.NET 10+)
- [ ] Structured logging is used consistently
- [ ] All exceptions are logged with context
- [ ] DEBUG-level logging implemented for critical operations
- [ ] Sensitive data (passwords) masked in logs
- [ ] Parameterized queries used for all database access
- [ ] Using statements for all disposables
- [ ] Theme support (dark/light mode) if applicable
